{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504102"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:10:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:10:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2297"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2297"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0.01,0.04,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112286"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1862"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46035"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112286"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old competitive runner presents with a three week history of worsening left foot pain. The pain is particularly worse when he gets out of bed in the morning and improves when he goes for walks. On examination, there is tenderness on palpation at the medial aspect of his hindfoot. On passive movement, dorsiflexion of the toes and foot this tenderness is increased. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the first-line management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol 1g QID, stretching, self-massage and heel insoles","Extracorporeal shockwave therapy","Urgent surgical referral","Arrange an elective osteotomy of the ankle in 6 weeks","Bed rest for 2 weeks"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows minor degenerative change between the intermediate and lateral cuneiform and first metatarsophalangeal joint. There is no focal cortical erosion. There is no significant calcaneal spur. The most likely condition affecting this patient is plantar fasciitis \u2013 an inflammation of the aponeurosis of its origin at the calcaneus. Risk factors include obesity, weight-bearing endurance exercise i.e. running and dancing. Plantar fasciitis presents as insidious sharp heel pain, often when getting out of bed in the morning. Patients may prefer walking on their toes initially, and the pain gets worse at the end of the day after prolonged standing. Physical examination suggests tenderness of palpation at the medial tuberosity of the calcaneus, dorsiflexion of the toes and foot increases with palpation. There is limited ankle dorsiflexion due to tight Achilles tendon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first-line management is primarily control of the pain with suitable \u003Cstrong\u003Eanalgesia and physical therapy which involves stretching and self-massage\u003C/strong\u003E. Heel insoles can also be used to provide support and relieve tension as the heel is raised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExtracorporeal shockwave therapy (ESWT)\u00a0for plantar fasciitis would be second-line management. Surgical interventions are rarely performed and only indicated if conservative management has failed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESteroid injections should very rarely be used for the increased risk of plantar fascia rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first line management of plantar fasciitis is pain control and stretching exercises."],"references":["Gill LH, Kiebzak GM. Outcome of nonsurgical treatment for plantar fasciitis. Foot Ankle Int 1996; 17:527.","D\u0027Ambrosia RD. Conservative management of metatarsal and heel pain in the adult foot. Orthopedics 1987; 10:137.","Aqil A, Siddiqui MR, Solan M, et al. Extracorporeal shock wave therapy is effective in treating chronic plantar fasciitis: a meta-analysis of RCTs. Clin Orthop Relat Res 2013; 471:3645."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2297"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17547"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17547"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8fd33ecb-6add-4d8d-b95a-3ab69231a6f0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8fd33ecb-6add-4d8d-b95a-3ab69231a6f0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":720,"height":334}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-28T09:02:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T09:04:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2297"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112286"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null